00:17:40.482 --> 00:17:41.640
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:17:41.640 --> 00:17:42.140
- Fact.

00:17:48.370 --> 00:17:50.410
This recent Super
Bowl, if you saw,

00:17:50.410 --> 00:17:51.940
there was a press
conference where

00:17:51.940 --> 00:17:55.840
Mayor Walsh-- and I was there
on stage interpreting with him.

00:17:55.840 --> 00:17:57.340
And that was very public.

00:17:57.340 --> 00:18:00.160
And it was edited where
someone grabbed a clip

00:18:00.160 --> 00:18:02.410
and put it online, on
reddit, and people were then

00:18:02.410 --> 00:18:05.980
started making various
comments about my look,

00:18:05.980 --> 00:18:08.440
my sexual performance,
what I looked like.

00:18:08.440 --> 00:18:09.700
The commentary went on and on.

00:18:09.700 --> 00:18:11.020
It was a free-for-all.

00:18:11.020 --> 00:18:14.200
But those were two examples
of me just as I am--

00:18:14.200 --> 00:18:14.950
Jackie.

00:18:14.950 --> 00:18:16.400
But it's not alone.

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:18.790
I'm not unique in
that one experience.

00:18:21.470 --> 00:18:23.520
So it's interesting
with this topic today,

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:28.530
and how we see women, and
how it impacts deaf men,

00:18:28.530 --> 00:18:30.993
and how it impacts deaf
youth who are boys.

00:18:30.993 --> 00:18:32.910
And that's what I want
to share with you guys.

00:18:36.670 --> 00:18:38.590
- So what was that like for you?

00:18:38.590 --> 00:18:40.120
Listening to me in
a conventionally

00:18:40.120 --> 00:18:45.800
accepted male voice, versus
now listening to me in my own?

00:18:45.800 --> 00:18:50.250
How does that difference
shape your judgments about me?

00:18:50.250 --> 00:18:52.920
About your willingness
to trust me, to hire me?

00:18:56.860 --> 00:18:59.230
I intentionally did not
ask you if that difference

00:18:59.230 --> 00:19:00.490
had an impact.

00:19:00.490 --> 00:19:02.830
For today, I want us to
examine that dynamic--

00:19:02.830 --> 00:19:05.020
when deaf boys and
men are working

00:19:05.020 --> 00:19:07.270
with female interpreters,
American Sign Language

00:19:07.270 --> 00:19:08.410
interpreters.

00:19:08.410 --> 00:19:11.830
And I want to challenge you to
examine your implicit biases

00:19:11.830 --> 00:19:14.830
and assess how, just as it
says here on the screen,

00:19:14.830 --> 00:19:17.800
how and to what degree that
experience of listening

00:19:17.800 --> 00:19:20.590
to a deaf man through
a female's voice

00:19:20.590 --> 00:19:29.010
is impacting your actions, and
what is your responsibility

00:19:29.010 --> 00:19:31.950
to make that connection
more authentic?

00:19:31.950 --> 00:19:33.870
So why does this matter?

00:19:33.870 --> 00:19:36.480
In 2016, a researcher
by the name of Punch,

00:19:36.480 --> 00:19:38.400
in her review of
literature, found

00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:40.320
that deaf people
were nearly two times

00:19:40.320 --> 00:19:43.530
as likely to be unemployed or
underemployed when compared

00:19:43.530 --> 00:19:46.020
to non-deaf individuals.

00:19:46.020 --> 00:19:48.540
And yet, when it
comes to one's career,

00:19:48.540 --> 00:19:52.470
a 2015 report from the Federal
Reserve Bank of New York

00:19:52.470 --> 00:19:53.880
put it bluntly.

00:19:53.880 --> 00:19:56.370
They said that your first
10 years in the labor market

00:19:56.370 --> 00:20:00.510
are likely to shape your entire
lifetime earning potential.

00:20:00.510 --> 00:20:02.550
So it's not
far-fetched to believe

00:20:02.550 --> 00:20:04.920
that because of society's
treatment of women,

00:20:04.920 --> 00:20:08.280
combined with the fact that 86%
of the people doing this work

00:20:08.280 --> 00:20:13.820
identify as female, is having
an impact on deaf men and boys

00:20:13.820 --> 00:20:15.930
and their social mobility--
their lifetime earning

00:20:15.930 --> 00:20:17.040
potential.

00:20:17.040 --> 00:20:19.290
And so that is the space
I want to invite you

00:20:19.290 --> 00:20:20.430
into today to explore.

00:20:26.530 --> 00:20:29.350
I have a few studies
to share to help

00:20:29.350 --> 00:20:30.910
illuminate further
why this topic is

00:20:30.910 --> 00:20:32.920
worth our consideration.

00:20:32.920 --> 00:20:34.800
As I share these,
I want you to think

00:20:34.800 --> 00:20:37.300
about listening to a deaf man
through a female interpreter's

00:20:37.300 --> 00:20:38.950
voice.

00:20:38.950 --> 00:20:42.880
In 2012, Karpowitz,
Mendelberg, and Shaker

00:20:42.880 --> 00:20:45.280
showed us that holding the
floor for a greater percentage

00:20:45.280 --> 00:20:47.050
of a group's
deliberation made you

00:20:47.050 --> 00:20:49.580
more likely to be seen as
influential in the group.

00:20:49.580 --> 00:20:52.570
However, if you were a
woman interrupting a man,

00:20:52.570 --> 00:20:55.000
you were likely to be
seen as disrespectful,

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:56.830
whereas a man
interrupting a woman

00:20:56.830 --> 00:20:59.260
was seen as more assertive.

00:20:59.260 --> 00:21:02.020
In a meta-analysis
of previous studies,

00:21:02.020 --> 00:21:04.420
Williams and Tiedens
in 2015 found

00:21:04.420 --> 00:21:06.160
that women who
assertively emphasized

00:21:06.160 --> 00:21:09.580
their skills, accomplishments,
or desire to lead,

00:21:09.580 --> 00:21:13.180
tended to be liked less and
to be seen as less hireable,

00:21:13.180 --> 00:21:17.600
compared to men describing
themselves identically.

00:21:17.600 --> 00:21:20.600
Specific to the work of
female ASL interpreters,

00:21:20.600 --> 00:21:24.170
Colleen Jones, in her
2017 graduate thesis work,

00:21:24.170 --> 00:21:27.440
found that non-deaf men who
were listening to deaf men

00:21:27.440 --> 00:21:29.300
through a female's
interpretation

00:21:29.300 --> 00:21:33.140
rated him as less intelligent
and less trustworthy as

00:21:33.140 --> 00:21:34.730
compared to
listening to deaf men

00:21:34.730 --> 00:21:37.130
through male
interpreters voices.

00:21:37.130 --> 00:21:41.690
And last, a 2018 study from
ASL interpreter Lena Jenny

00:21:41.690 --> 00:21:43.370
looked into
genderqueer and female

00:21:43.370 --> 00:21:49.485
presenting interpreters with
masculine tethered traits.

00:21:49.485 --> 00:21:51.110
And she found that
if you are masculine

00:21:51.110 --> 00:21:54.080
presenting and utilize
masculine discourse traits,

00:21:54.080 --> 00:21:56.600
you may actually be compounding
the discrimination faced

00:21:56.600 --> 00:21:58.920
by these deaf men.

00:21:58.920 --> 00:22:01.135
So let's see if we
have this so far.

00:22:01.135 --> 00:22:02.510
If we're masculine
presenting, we

00:22:02.510 --> 00:22:03.985
need to try to
sound more feminine.

00:22:03.985 --> 00:22:05.360
But if we're
feminine presenting,

00:22:05.360 --> 00:22:08.042
we need to try to
sound more masculine.

00:22:08.042 --> 00:22:10.250
All women should probably
try to sound more masculine

00:22:10.250 --> 00:22:11.480
when other men are listening.

00:22:11.480 --> 00:22:12.800
But don't interrupt men.

00:22:12.800 --> 00:22:13.360
Right?

00:22:13.360 --> 00:22:14.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:15.140
Got it.

00:22:15.140 --> 00:22:17.900
When it's all women, we can
sound authoritative, but not

00:22:17.900 --> 00:22:18.980
tout our accomplishments.

00:22:18.980 --> 00:22:21.438
And when men are listening, or
when we're in mixed company,

00:22:21.438 --> 00:22:24.435
we need to tone it down, but
be ready to celebrate ourselves

00:22:24.435 --> 00:22:25.310
in a moment's notice.

00:22:25.310 --> 00:22:26.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:26.260 --> 00:22:28.160
Got it.

00:22:28.160 --> 00:22:30.290
So, because we are
damned if we do,

00:22:30.290 --> 00:22:33.440
and damned if we don't,
as was just shown,

00:22:33.440 --> 00:22:35.600
many female interpreters
report using

00:22:35.600 --> 00:22:38.060
any of the following
compensatory strategies.

00:22:38.060 --> 00:22:39.680
We stand taller,
we lower our voices

00:22:39.680 --> 00:22:43.370
during the interpretation,
we dress in neutral attire

00:22:43.370 --> 00:22:45.260
that we think is
more androgynous.

00:22:45.260 --> 00:22:47.260
Although I just learned
in the last presentation

00:22:47.260 --> 00:22:49.135
it's actually more
masculine, which is really

00:22:49.135 --> 00:22:50.690
screwing with my mind.

00:22:50.690 --> 00:22:52.250
Thank you.

00:22:52.250 --> 00:22:53.780
We maintain distant
attitudes, we

00:22:53.780 --> 00:22:55.880
learn to interrupt
to claim the floor,

00:22:55.880 --> 00:22:58.160
and we train
ourselves to eliminate

00:22:58.160 --> 00:23:01.100
what is conventionally
known as powerless language.

00:23:01.100 --> 00:23:02.960
Folks, we do all of
this while navigating

00:23:02.960 --> 00:23:06.830
one of the most cognitively
complex tasks out there.

00:23:06.830 --> 00:23:08.570
This is the world
of ASL interpreting,

00:23:08.570 --> 00:23:11.940
through the lens of a
female ASL interpreter.

00:23:11.940 --> 00:23:13.400
I want to take a step back.

00:23:13.400 --> 00:23:15.150
So we just covered a
little bit about what

00:23:15.150 --> 00:23:17.040
female interpreters
are up against,

00:23:17.040 --> 00:23:19.765
but I want you to
understand what you--

00:23:19.765 --> 00:23:21.390
I want to know what
your experience is.

00:23:21.390 --> 00:23:25.080
When you hire an ASL
interpreter, what's that like?

00:23:25.080 --> 00:23:26.607
We'll take a broad
stroke here, just

00:23:26.607 --> 00:23:28.440
so we can appreciate
where the daily reality

00:23:28.440 --> 00:23:31.080
of deaf men and female ASL
interpreters is situated.

00:23:34.160 --> 00:23:36.260
ASL interpreting as
a profession was not

00:23:36.260 --> 00:23:38.595
known in the United
States until 1964,

00:23:38.595 --> 00:23:40.220
which is when our
National Professional

00:23:40.220 --> 00:23:42.860
Organization, the Registry
of Interpreters for the Deaf,

00:23:42.860 --> 00:23:44.161
was established.

00:23:46.750 --> 00:23:48.460
We are predominantly female.

00:23:48.460 --> 00:23:51.610
As was mentioned,
86% of RID members

00:23:51.610 --> 00:23:56.060
who chose to identify
a gender are female.

00:23:56.060 --> 00:23:58.050
We are overwhelmingly white.

00:23:58.050 --> 00:24:01.610
87% of us doing this
work identify as white.

00:24:01.610 --> 00:24:04.160
And this is why you'll see
in my presentation today,

00:24:04.160 --> 00:24:07.417
the majority of my photos
are of white professionals.

00:24:07.417 --> 00:24:09.500
Because that's the reality
that we're up against--

00:24:09.500 --> 00:24:11.330
that folks are dealing
with-- even though we are not

00:24:11.330 --> 00:24:13.310
representative of the
increasingly diverse

00:24:13.310 --> 00:24:14.740
populations of whom we serve.

00:24:17.290 --> 00:24:23.740
At least 93% of our members
are second or other language

00:24:23.740 --> 00:24:25.790
learners of American
Sign Language.

00:24:25.790 --> 00:24:26.290
OK.

00:24:26.290 --> 00:24:28.300
So that's the larger context.

00:24:28.300 --> 00:24:30.970
We're a young profession,
we are predominantly female

00:24:30.970 --> 00:24:33.460
white women, and we have
come into the language

00:24:33.460 --> 00:24:36.280
in the community as guests,
or second and other language

00:24:36.280 --> 00:24:38.350
learners of ASL, present
company included.

00:24:41.300 --> 00:24:43.212
Now that you have a
sense of who we are,

00:24:43.212 --> 00:24:45.670
I want to look at some of the
commonly reported experiences

00:24:45.670 --> 00:24:47.680
of this predominately
female workforce

00:24:47.680 --> 00:24:51.710
when working with men.

00:24:51.710 --> 00:24:55.250
Deaf and non-deaf men alike
routinely apologize to us

00:24:55.250 --> 00:24:56.742
when they drop f-bombs.

00:24:56.742 --> 00:24:57.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:57.980 --> 00:24:59.540
Now, when men are
with other men,

00:24:59.540 --> 00:25:03.380
we know that they swear to
decrease social distance,

00:25:03.380 --> 00:25:04.768
for social power.

00:25:04.768 --> 00:25:07.310
So if they're censoring their
speech because of our presence,

00:25:07.310 --> 00:25:09.140
how does that impact
their interaction

00:25:09.140 --> 00:25:10.280
and its authenticity?

00:25:13.430 --> 00:25:15.550
Now, this happens in
one-on-one interactions.

00:25:15.550 --> 00:25:18.760
It also happens in larger
all-male only spaces.

00:25:18.760 --> 00:25:21.460
The entire dynamic will shift
if I, or any of my sister

00:25:21.460 --> 00:25:24.070
interpreters, walk into
a fraternity event,

00:25:24.070 --> 00:25:27.070
or an all-male sex offender
group therapy session,

00:25:27.070 --> 00:25:30.040
or a deaf man
wanting to find out

00:25:30.040 --> 00:25:31.870
what's up with his male doctor.

00:25:31.870 --> 00:25:33.400
Right?

00:25:33.400 --> 00:25:35.950
So, considering the reality
that less than 14% of my field

00:25:35.950 --> 00:25:39.100
identifies as male, what
other strategies can we,

00:25:39.100 --> 00:25:41.770
and you who work
with us, what can you

00:25:41.770 --> 00:25:43.540
do to level the playing field?

00:25:46.300 --> 00:25:46.800
All right.

00:25:46.800 --> 00:25:47.402
Picture this.

00:25:47.402 --> 00:25:49.110
You're a college
student, you're enrolled

00:25:49.110 --> 00:25:51.485
in one of the interpreting
programs in the United States,

00:25:51.485 --> 00:25:53.970
and your college announces
that a very well-known comedian

00:25:53.970 --> 00:25:55.960
is coming to campus.

00:25:55.960 --> 00:25:57.210
Interpreters will be provided.

00:25:57.210 --> 00:25:59.010
So naturally, you
buy tickets, right?

00:25:59.010 --> 00:26:00.810
You want to see a
real-life interpretation,

00:26:00.810 --> 00:26:02.730
you want to hone your
understanding of ASL,

00:26:02.730 --> 00:26:05.640
and dream about one day being
hired as a professional sign

00:26:05.640 --> 00:26:06.730
language interpreter.

00:26:06.730 --> 00:26:07.230
OK.

00:26:07.230 --> 00:26:09.090
So the show starts,
and at some point

00:26:09.090 --> 00:26:11.707
the comedian suddenly takes
notice of the female ASL

00:26:11.707 --> 00:26:12.540
interpreter working.

00:26:12.540 --> 00:26:15.870
In fact, you might have
seen these clips on YouTube.

00:26:15.870 --> 00:26:17.530
He tries to get a
rise out of her.

00:26:17.530 --> 00:26:19.530
He starts using obscene
language that I will not

00:26:19.530 --> 00:26:22.317
use today out of respect
for my colleague working.

00:26:22.317 --> 00:26:24.150
But the interpreter
maintains her composure,

00:26:24.150 --> 00:26:26.730
interpreting every single jab
that comes at her expense.

00:26:26.730 --> 00:26:29.230
And you can't help but think,
sitting there in the audience,

00:26:29.230 --> 00:26:31.440
is this what you're aspiring
to be when you grow up?

00:26:31.440 --> 00:26:34.740
Exploited for a cheap laugh and
used in public, or anywhere?

00:26:38.640 --> 00:26:41.670
This situation is not unique to
that individual I just shared.

00:26:41.670 --> 00:26:49.080
It's one that many of us
have found ourselves in.

00:26:49.080 --> 00:26:51.288
Consider the reddit example
that I mentioned earlier.

00:26:51.288 --> 00:26:52.747
It turns out,
though, that it's not

00:26:52.747 --> 00:26:55.380
just the ignorant public who
sexualized female interpreters.

00:26:55.380 --> 00:26:57.750
In 2008, a video relay
service provider,

00:26:57.750 --> 00:27:00.660
one of the largest employers
of interpreters nationwide,

00:27:00.660 --> 00:27:04.110
denied its female
interpreters, its employees,

00:27:04.110 --> 00:27:06.800
the option of disconnecting
from a serial predator

00:27:06.800 --> 00:27:08.550
who would connect with
them on the webcam,

00:27:08.550 --> 00:27:13.160
not to place a phone call, but
