yours to educate, and where
do you see the line between it

00:38:26.740 --> 00:38:28.352
really isn't you're
responsibility?

00:38:32.690 --> 00:38:35.980
- For thoughts on that,
I think it would really

00:38:35.980 --> 00:38:39.220
depend on the environment.

00:38:39.220 --> 00:38:41.800
When you're dealing in
a personal situation

00:38:41.800 --> 00:38:44.380
where it is a
medical appointment,

00:38:44.380 --> 00:38:46.540
I think it's medical
related, medical issues.

00:38:46.540 --> 00:38:49.300
I want to focus on that
information as opposed

00:38:49.300 --> 00:38:52.210
to being an educator
in role at that time.

00:38:52.210 --> 00:38:53.320
I'm a patient.

00:38:53.320 --> 00:38:55.240
So for the patient
to then explain, oh,

00:38:55.240 --> 00:38:56.300
this is the role
of the interpreter,

00:38:56.300 --> 00:38:57.800
this is the role
of you as a doctor.

00:38:57.800 --> 00:38:58.580
No.

00:38:58.580 --> 00:39:01.750
You know, as opposed to,
in a different environment

00:39:01.750 --> 00:39:06.710
or context, as an example,
like a IEP meeting.

00:39:06.710 --> 00:39:10.550
So in a K through
12 situation where

00:39:10.550 --> 00:39:12.740
there might be an
opportunity there to explain

00:39:12.740 --> 00:39:15.110
about the communication roles.

00:39:15.110 --> 00:39:18.440
And again, the objective is to
get the results that I want.

00:39:18.440 --> 00:39:21.010
So I have to kind
of walk that line.

00:39:21.010 --> 00:39:23.390
Again, just, what
the overall objective

00:39:23.390 --> 00:39:25.670
is in working and
interacting with me.

00:39:25.670 --> 00:39:27.480
So sometimes it's an
educational roles,

00:39:27.480 --> 00:39:29.960
sometimes an advocate
role, sometimes it's

00:39:29.960 --> 00:39:31.970
me to step back and just be me.

00:39:31.970 --> 00:39:35.164
So it's like, hey, that's
your job, not mine.

00:39:35.164 --> 00:39:38.000
- Great.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:40.345
In line with Jackie's
comment around what can we

00:39:40.345 --> 00:39:41.720
do to be active
around that, I do

00:39:41.720 --> 00:39:44.990
want to applaud Radcliffe
for inviting ASL interpreters

00:39:44.990 --> 00:39:47.990
and having interpretation
at a lot of their events.

00:39:47.990 --> 00:39:50.135
And to reiterate,
both to Radcliffe,

00:39:50.135 --> 00:39:52.010
and then, any others
who are planning events,

00:39:52.010 --> 00:39:54.770
that when you have that
available, it really does

00:39:54.770 --> 00:39:56.810
increase the
likelihood, both of that

00:39:56.810 --> 00:39:58.723
deaf individuals can come--

00:39:58.723 --> 00:40:00.890
sometimes people say, well
nobody's asked us for it.

00:40:00.890 --> 00:40:02.973
But they might not know
that that's a possibility.

00:40:02.973 --> 00:40:05.498
So by arranging that and making
communication accessible,

00:40:05.498 --> 00:40:07.040
I think that's a
very important thing

00:40:07.040 --> 00:40:08.510
that we can do to be proactive.

00:40:11.030 --> 00:40:13.550
And it also increases
visibility, and awareness,

00:40:13.550 --> 00:40:17.240
and access in ways that
are really important.

00:40:17.240 --> 00:40:19.370
With that, I'm going to
open it up for questions.

00:40:19.370 --> 00:40:21.050
As others have
said, please join us

00:40:21.050 --> 00:40:28.370
in the center to ask a question
and our speakers will respond.

00:40:28.370 --> 00:40:30.710
- Thank you so much for
helping me understand

00:40:30.710 --> 00:40:34.670
the way that gender is
based on location in so much

00:40:34.670 --> 00:40:35.420
of the signs.

00:40:35.420 --> 00:40:40.100
But I'm curious about the way
that gender accidentally works

00:40:40.100 --> 00:40:41.900
its way into speech and sign.

00:40:41.900 --> 00:40:45.050
In the way that, kind of,
declarative statements

00:40:45.050 --> 00:40:48.170
tend to be read as more a
kind of a male speech pattern,

00:40:48.170 --> 00:40:50.330
and interrogative
statements tend

00:40:50.330 --> 00:40:52.310
to be read as more of a
female speech pattern.

00:40:52.310 --> 00:40:55.130
I'm wondering, what
are the accidental tics

00:40:55.130 --> 00:40:58.880
inside a sign that could
show unintentional ways that

00:40:58.880 --> 00:41:02.270
gender has kind of
woven its way into sign?

00:41:08.937 --> 00:41:11.020
- It's going to get another
interpretation of that

00:41:11.020 --> 00:41:12.687
because that is a
deep concept for sure.

00:41:15.960 --> 00:41:16.782
Jackie?

00:41:16.782 --> 00:41:19.560
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:19.560 --> 00:41:24.110
- So one example,
and please, Rosa Lee,

00:41:24.110 --> 00:41:25.110
correct me if I'm wrong.

00:41:25.110 --> 00:41:29.710
So the sign as we talked about
mother or father, mom or dad,

00:41:29.710 --> 00:41:36.490
but now in the LGBTQ community,
any of non-binary individuals.

00:41:36.490 --> 00:41:39.070
So it's like mom, mom so
it's kind of like, all right,

00:41:39.070 --> 00:41:40.390
how are we going to sign that?

00:41:40.390 --> 00:41:44.680
Dad, dad, or in the
middle of those two

00:41:44.680 --> 00:41:46.960
established locations?

00:41:46.960 --> 00:41:51.740
So just as an example like that
that has that attributed to it.

00:41:51.740 --> 00:41:54.670
So, parents is signed like this.

00:41:54.670 --> 00:41:57.680
So if you had two
moms, then it's like,

00:41:57.680 --> 00:42:00.900
are you going to not go
up to the higher location

00:42:00.900 --> 00:42:03.750
for that sign that
is indicating parent?

00:42:03.750 --> 00:42:07.100
So also in this region
here, around your nose,

00:42:07.100 --> 00:42:09.780
it's typically negative.

00:42:09.780 --> 00:42:13.590
Something that is
lousy, smells, stinks.

00:42:13.590 --> 00:42:15.150
Actually this is
a sign for penis,

00:42:15.150 --> 00:42:16.920
since we were on that
topic today earlier.

00:42:16.920 --> 00:42:18.640
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:18.640 --> 00:42:20.830
Just the nose.

00:42:20.830 --> 00:42:21.330
All right.

00:42:21.330 --> 00:42:23.910
Well, just, anyways, it's
not really a positive place.

00:42:23.910 --> 00:42:27.240
So it's just kind of
maybe around this region

00:42:27.240 --> 00:42:28.740
or this location.

00:42:28.740 --> 00:42:31.620
So there has been some
discourse as far as

00:42:31.620 --> 00:42:34.200
whether that is a positive
or negative attribute

00:42:34.200 --> 00:42:35.100
of that location.

00:42:35.100 --> 00:42:38.475
But again, it's something that
is very fluid and evolving.

00:42:38.475 --> 00:42:40.350
And over time, we will
get to the right sign.

00:42:40.350 --> 00:42:43.210
So, definitely.

00:42:43.210 --> 00:42:47.940
- And if I could add just from
an interpreter perspective.

00:42:47.940 --> 00:42:50.570
I-- I'm sorry?

00:42:50.570 --> 00:42:51.070
That's OK.

00:42:51.070 --> 00:42:52.360
- Just one moment
for the interpreter.

00:42:52.360 --> 00:42:52.860
Thanks.

00:42:52.860 --> 00:42:56.310
- I have one perspective
from the interpreting world.

00:42:56.310 --> 00:43:00.360
So in ASL, pronominalization
is gender neutral.

00:43:00.360 --> 00:43:02.780
And so, when you're an
interpreter working with a deaf

00:43:02.780 --> 00:43:04.910
individual who's referring
to someone in space,

00:43:04.910 --> 00:43:06.350
but they haven't told
you their gender--

00:43:06.350 --> 00:43:08.060
they haven't told you
anything about them--

00:43:08.060 --> 00:43:09.920
you as the interpreter then
have to make that decision.

00:43:09.920 --> 00:43:11.750
There are so many different
strategies we use.

00:43:11.750 --> 00:43:13.708
Sometimes we get our foot
caught in our mouths,

00:43:13.708 --> 00:43:16.130
where we assign a gender
to someone who we think,

00:43:16.130 --> 00:43:18.320
and then we end up having
to backtrack and own

00:43:18.320 --> 00:43:19.450
that error as well.

00:43:19.450 --> 00:43:21.900
But, specific to the language,
that shows up in our work

00:43:21.900 --> 00:43:22.400
as well.

00:43:25.700 --> 00:43:27.980
- One interesting thing
about American Sign Language

00:43:27.980 --> 00:43:31.430
is this right here, this
indication using as pronoun

00:43:31.430 --> 00:43:35.330
is actually very neutral,
which works for an interpreter,

00:43:35.330 --> 00:43:37.040
as Jackie just mentioned.

00:43:37.040 --> 00:43:41.180
And I could sign this and
be like, it was he, or she,

00:43:41.180 --> 00:43:43.370
or this person told me,
or this person told me.

00:43:43.370 --> 00:43:46.688
So that's one example of
that neutral language.

00:43:46.688 --> 00:43:48.230
And that's more work
for you, Jackie.

00:43:48.230 --> 00:43:48.730
Sorry.

00:43:51.590 --> 00:43:53.684
Does that answer your question?

00:43:53.684 --> 00:43:55.360
- It's a little bit different.

00:43:55.360 --> 00:43:56.200
But it's OK--

00:43:56.200 --> 00:43:57.210
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:43:57.210 --> 00:43:59.340
- I guess what I mean
is, could you show us

00:43:59.340 --> 00:44:04.075
the difference between the way
a man might sign something that

00:44:04.075 --> 00:44:06.600
shows more power
in the situation?

00:44:06.600 --> 00:44:09.080
But it's not about the
words they're using,

00:44:09.080 --> 00:44:11.850
it's about the way
the sign looks.

00:44:11.850 --> 00:44:17.090
With more certainty,
versus with more, kind of,

00:44:17.090 --> 00:44:18.660
you know, questioning.

00:44:18.660 --> 00:44:21.360
Or lack of confidence
or something.

00:44:21.360 --> 00:44:23.640
Could you show us
the way that gender

00:44:23.640 --> 00:44:26.100
might be embodied in
a particular sign that

00:44:26.100 --> 00:44:28.950
might show the difference
between the way power

00:44:28.950 --> 00:44:33.050
is encoded into the performance
of a particular sign?

00:44:38.160 --> 00:44:40.300
- I would say with facial
expressions is probably

00:44:40.300 --> 00:44:42.820
the parameter I would refer to.

00:44:42.820 --> 00:44:46.500
Eye gaze and glance.

00:44:46.500 --> 00:44:51.200
Like this, where your
eyes are looking downward.

00:44:51.200 --> 00:44:56.440
The use of hands
like this that is

00:44:56.440 --> 00:44:59.380
indicating a status or class.

00:44:59.380 --> 00:45:04.450
Or as opposed to doing
this, ask her, or he.

00:45:04.450 --> 00:45:09.500
So again, that could then refer
again to a status in class.

00:45:09.500 --> 00:45:12.620
So location that way is
one way of indicating that.

00:45:12.620 --> 00:45:15.490
So there is a way
of inferring it.

00:45:15.490 --> 00:45:17.070
So there's a lot of -ists.

00:45:17.070 --> 00:45:19.980
Oddist attitude,
racist attitude,

00:45:19.980 --> 00:45:22.740
whatever the case may be
within the diverse community.

00:45:22.740 --> 00:45:24.870
As it is in society,
as diverse as it

00:45:24.870 --> 00:45:30.450
is to indicate that status,
just by that range of height

00:45:30.450 --> 00:45:31.830
and location.

00:45:31.830 --> 00:45:36.270
Also assign, also
being conveyed--

00:45:36.270 --> 00:45:41.700
very small signing space or a
large signing space, like this.

00:45:44.380 --> 00:45:46.800
So those are other
ways within, again,

00:45:46.800 --> 00:45:48.960
how you morph along
those parameters.

00:45:48.960 --> 00:45:52.400
And slight changes can
indicate that power and control

00:45:52.400 --> 00:45:54.945
and status as an example.

00:45:54.945 --> 00:45:57.700
Does that work for you?

00:45:57.700 --> 00:45:58.200
All right.

00:45:58.200 --> 00:45:58.490
Great.

00:45:58.490 --> 00:45:59.590
- Next question please.

00:45:59.590 --> 00:46:01.320
- So interesting.

00:46:01.320 --> 00:46:04.800
I had a question about
the idea of seeing women

00:46:04.800 --> 00:46:10.740
in positions of authority and
is there a corollary view?

00:46:10.740 --> 00:46:15.630
I understand the idea of
the gendered interpretation

00:46:15.630 --> 00:46:20.460
upon males, for instance,
having a female signer,

00:46:20.460 --> 00:46:25.530
and that sexist interpretation
that's coming from the hearing

00:46:25.530 --> 00:46:26.130
community.

00:46:26.130 --> 00:46:32.130
But is there a corollary
impact of boys growing up

00:46:32.130 --> 00:46:34.320
seeing women in
authoritative positions

00:46:34.320 --> 00:46:39.030
that actually empowers a kind
of more equal gender dynamic

00:46:39.030 --> 00:46:40.875
within the deaf community?

00:46:44.340 --> 00:46:49.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:49.290 --> 00:46:52.040
- That's a new research
project for Jackie to take on.

00:46:52.040 --> 00:46:53.070
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:53.070 --> 00:46:57.040
That is a great, great question.

00:46:57.040 --> 00:46:59.430
- So maybe I would
then counter that

00:46:59.430 --> 00:47:04.860
and say, is the societal
view of sexist perspective,

00:47:04.860 --> 00:47:06.760
is that paralleled in
the deaf community?

00:47:06.760 --> 00:47:09.120
And I would say
that it is the same.

00:47:09.120 --> 00:47:12.540
So there is a -ist-- a sexist.

00:47:12.540 --> 00:47:15.540
So if you have that,
it doesn't really

00:47:15.540 --> 00:47:19.340
matter if the person
is deaf or hearing,

00:47:19.340 --> 00:47:22.220
whether that is impacted
in that dynamic.

00:47:22.220 --> 00:47:25.910
Because the person is female,
or identifies as female, and is

00:47:25.910 --> 00:47:26.960
Caucasian.

00:47:26.960 --> 00:47:28.430
Would that make
them less sexist?

00:47:28.430 --> 00:47:29.390
I don't know.

00:47:29.390 --> 00:47:31.698
That could be a great
research topic though.

00:47:31.698 --> 00:47:33.740
- I can add, just from a
developmental psychology

00:47:33.740 --> 00:47:36.980
perspective, that the idea for
young boys, elementary age,

00:47:36.980 --> 00:47:39.650
for example, the way that
they connect with teachers

00:47:39.650 --> 00:47:42.050
and paraprofessionals,
looking up to them

00:47:42.050 --> 00:47:44.070
and feeling that connection
with their teacher.

00:47:44.070 --> 00:47:45.530
But we definitely see--

00:47:45.530 --> 00:47:47.728
in a clinical view--

00:47:47.728 --> 00:47:49.520
adolescents, middle
school, high schoolers,

00:47:49.520 --> 00:47:50.690
who then have to rely on that.

00:47:50.690 --> 00:47:52.070
They think it is a
very different kind

00:47:52.070 --> 00:47:52.980
of a relationship.

00:47:52.980 --> 00:47:56.140
So in part, it might be, here's
another nurturing person who

00:47:56.140 --> 00:47:58.280
is involved in your
life, which can be great,

00:47:58.280 --> 00:48:00.560
and a resistance to feeling--

00:48:00.560 --> 00:48:03.350
to needing that later on.

00:48:03.350 --> 00:48:03.850
- Thank you.

00:48:03.850 --> 00:48:06.158
- Mm-hmm.

00:48:06.158 --> 00:48:06.658
Yes.

00:48:09.470 --> 00:48:12.420
We need voice
interpretation please.

00:48:12.420 --> 00:48:17.510
- Oh I'm just asking you to come
up here so everyone can see.

00:48:17.510 --> 00:48:18.010
- Hi guys.

00:48:21.247 --> 00:48:23.205
I'm just going to kind
of throw this out there.

00:48:30.810 --> 00:48:34.690
So an event where you have, as
an example, Martin Luther King.

00:48:34.690 --> 00:48:37.170
There is an event with MLK Day.

00:48:37.170 --> 00:48:39.060
And then you have
an individual who's

00:48:39.060 --> 00:48:41.070
assigned as the interpreter.

00:48:41.070 --> 00:48:42.810
How are they going
to handle that where

00:48:42.810 --> 00:48:46.020
they're white, female, as
opposed to being someone

00:48:46.020 --> 00:48:47.080
who is a person of color?

00:48:49.740 --> 00:48:52.350
Now, how does that go as
far as the perspective

00:48:52.350 --> 00:48:54.630
of assigning that person?

00:48:54.630 --> 00:48:55.860
Is there an option?

00:48:55.860 --> 00:48:58.620
And which one would you pick,
and which one should I pick?

00:48:58.620 --> 00:49:01.890
Should it be the person who is
of color, just because they're

00:49:01.890 --> 00:49:03.233
of color?

00:49:03.233 --> 00:49:04.650
Just kind of throw
that out there.

00:49:04.650 --> 00:49:06.570
And you might not
have a response,

00:49:06.570 --> 00:49:10.810
but it might come down
to resource availability.

00:49:10.810 --> 00:49:12.030
So just a thought about that?

00:49:17.437 --> 00:49:19.520
- I would say that in the
industry of interpreting

00:49:19.520 --> 00:49:22.670
as a profession,
it's been terrible--

00:49:22.670 --> 00:49:26.210
to be quite honest-- with
interpreters of color.

00:49:26.210 --> 00:49:29.620
And sometimes to say, hey, we
want to grow that population

00:49:29.620 --> 00:49:31.100
and that demographic.

00:49:31.100 --> 00:49:33.830
But to really
actually proactively

00:49:33.830 --> 00:49:37.430
go out to that community
as a professional--

00:49:37.430 --> 00:49:40.040
as a profession-- we
haven't done that yet.

00:49:40.040 --> 00:49:42.680
And it's really-- it's overdue.

00:49:42.680 --> 00:49:44.420
It's past time.

00:49:44.420 --> 00:49:47.330
We hope that's something
that will take on.

00:49:47.330 --> 00:49:51.170
There is a grant, a
Project Klein, actually.

00:49:51.170 --> 00:49:54.410
And that is trying to increase
the working population

00:49:54.410 --> 00:49:58.310
of interpreters of color
to do legal work as part

00:49:58.310 --> 00:50:00.650
of their professional
development.

00:50:00.650 --> 00:50:03.680
You know, working
in courts, you never

00:50:03.680 --> 00:50:05.270
think about, like,
OK, well, this

00:50:05.270 --> 00:50:08.150
might not be fair for
how I'm representing.

00:50:08.150 --> 00:50:11.060
And really thinking about--
it's supposed to be justice.

00:50:11.060 --> 00:50:14.210
It's justice within the justice
system, if you think about it.

00:50:14.210 --> 00:50:16.283
So it's a double
layer there as it is.

00:50:16.283 --> 00:50:18.200
So whether it's dealing
in the justice system,

00:50:18.200 --> 00:50:21.020
or whether it's dealing in
the health care environment,

00:50:21.020 --> 00:50:21.890
it's time.

00:50:21.890 --> 00:50:23.130
It's overdue for sure.

00:50:23.130 --> 00:50:25.850
And thank you for
bringing that up.

00:50:25.850 --> 00:50:28.060
- Also, if I could
comment on that.

00:50:28.060 --> 00:50:33.510
As far as manipulating the
results, if I could say,

00:50:33.510 --> 00:50:36.690
as a black hearing
individual who's

00:50:36.690 --> 00:50:42.010
speaking to an audience of
white or Caucasian individuals,

00:50:42.010 --> 00:50:45.820
they would prefer to have
a white male interpreter.

00:50:45.820 --> 00:50:50.340
Because in that way,
there's a relatability

00:50:50.340 --> 00:50:52.800
And see that common
ground, which

00:50:52.800 --> 00:50:58.830
then triggers an allyship, which
then triggers active listening.

00:50:58.830 --> 00:51:00.410
So then you have
a black audience,

00:51:00.410 --> 00:51:05.030
or having that opportunity
to have a person of color

00:51:05.030 --> 00:51:07.850
in the audience, and then
having that same demographic

00:51:07.850 --> 00:51:09.320
represented by the interpreter.

00:51:09.320 --> 00:51:13.010
So again, it does depend on
the result, and the objective,

00:51:13.010 --> 00:51:14.665
and what you're looking for.

00:51:14.665 --> 00:51:16.040
So that would
impact the judgment

00:51:16.040 --> 00:51:19.100
in the decision of whether you
were getting a person of color,

00:51:19.100 --> 00:51:23.708
or a Caucasian, a male, or
female identifying interpreter.

00:51:23.708 --> 00:51:25.250
- I would add that
people like Jackie

00:51:25.250 --> 00:51:29.420
are very conscientious of that
and the choice might sometimes

00:51:29.420 --> 00:51:31.580
be, well, I'd prefer to
have another person do it,

00:51:31.580 --> 00:51:34.130
but if it means there's going
to be no interpreter present,

00:51:34.130 --> 00:51:34.880
I'll take the job.

00:51:37.490 --> 00:51:38.833
Yeah.

00:51:38.833 --> 00:51:39.500
- Next question.

00:51:39.500 --> 00:51:40.040
- Yes.

00:51:40.040 --> 00:51:40.808
Go ahead.

00:51:40.808 --> 00:51:41.600
- Thank all of you.

00:51:41.600 --> 00:51:42.710
This is so wonderful.

00:51:42.710 --> 00:51:44.210
All of you.

00:51:44.210 --> 00:51:47.650
My question is about
getting older and using ASL.

00:51:47.650 --> 00:51:50.460
And I'm so impressed with
the physical vitality,

00:51:50.460 --> 00:51:54.410
the manual dexterity this
beautiful language asks of you.

00:51:54.410 --> 00:51:56.510
But I'm trying to
imagine my mother who

00:51:56.510 --> 00:51:58.455
has arthritis doing this.

00:51:58.455 --> 00:52:00.080
And so, it's sort of
me thinking about,

00:52:00.080 --> 00:52:01.760
what happens as you get older?

00:52:01.760 --> 00:52:07.380
Perhaps you lose a partner
who is also your interpreter?

00:52:07.380 --> 00:52:11.180
And also curious, do you lose
words the same way that I'm

00:52:11.180 --> 00:52:12.170
starting to lose words.

00:52:12.170 --> 00:52:13.628
You know, you're
reaching for them.

00:52:13.628 --> 00:52:16.330
I'm curious about the
process of aging with ASL.

00:52:27.770 --> 00:52:31.220
- As I mentioned, those
five fundamental parameters,

00:52:31.220 --> 00:52:32.900
you can't live without those.

00:52:32.900 --> 00:52:35.240
So, you can't do it if you
don't have the hand shape.

00:52:35.240 --> 00:52:37.640
You can't convey the language.

00:52:37.640 --> 00:52:39.390
But, you have those
four other parameters.

00:52:39.390 --> 00:52:42.780
Would you be able to use
those to convey something?

00:52:42.780 --> 00:52:44.400
If you do have
movement, you could

00:52:44.400 --> 00:52:45.600
recognize there is movement.

00:52:45.600 --> 00:52:47.760
But without the
hand shape, it then

00:52:47.760 --> 00:52:49.650
indicates something different.

00:52:49.650 --> 00:52:52.650
So trying to adjust.

00:52:52.650 --> 00:52:55.290
As an example, my
grandfather is deaf.

00:52:55.290 --> 00:52:58.955
And he signs very low, like
this, in the signing space.

00:52:58.955 --> 00:53:00.330
And I'm trying to
understand him.

00:53:00.330 --> 00:53:01.580
I'm like, raise your hands up.

00:53:01.580 --> 00:53:03.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:03.020 --> 00:53:04.810
He's signing so
low in that space.

00:53:04.810 --> 00:53:07.770
But over time, I've
gotten used to him

00:53:07.770 --> 00:53:12.870
and his mannerisms, his
use of space, location,

00:53:12.870 --> 00:53:16.650
and I know what he's indicating.

00:53:16.650 --> 00:53:19.660
Sometimes there's some
guesswork involved, you know,

00:53:19.660 --> 00:53:21.600
and I'm trying to like,
all right, I think

00:53:21.600 --> 00:53:22.930
that's what you're saying.

00:53:22.930 --> 00:53:24.870
Which would be no
different than you

00:53:24.870 --> 00:53:27.078
as you're interacting with
someone else who's hearing

00:53:27.078 --> 00:53:28.780
in the spoken language.

00:53:28.780 --> 00:53:31.947
So, I guess, trying to
convey that language.

00:53:31.947 --> 00:53:34.030
If you have a weakness in
one of those parameters,

00:53:34.030 --> 00:53:35.738
the other parts of
those other parameters

00:53:35.738 --> 00:53:37.555
can then reinforce that.

00:53:37.555 --> 00:53:39.930
- I want to talk about the
practical implications of that

00:53:39.930 --> 00:53:41.970
too, working as a
hearing interpreter--

00:53:41.970 --> 00:53:44.760
non-deaf interpreter
with aging populations.

00:53:44.760 --> 00:53:47.100
Because so many of us have
come into this language

00:53:47.100 --> 00:53:49.770
as second language
learners, we miss nuance.

00:53:49.770 --> 00:53:52.880
We are never going to be
100% native in what we do.

00:53:52.880 --> 00:53:53.520
Right?

00:53:53.520 --> 00:53:56.910
And so, fortunately, we
have tandem colleagues

00:53:56.910 --> 00:53:58.200
who are deaf themselves.

00:53:58.200 --> 00:54:02.698
Language professionals, who
we refer to as Certified Deaf

00:54:02.698 --> 00:54:05.240
Interpreters, who are going to
be these language specialists.

00:54:05.240 --> 00:54:07.573
Grew up in this world, visually
acquainted to the world.

00:54:07.573 --> 00:54:10.170
Just like these
aging individuals

00:54:10.170 --> 00:54:12.840
you were mentioning,
who, for the arthritic

00:54:12.840 --> 00:54:15.630
hands, who are missing
parameters, or what have you.

00:54:15.630 --> 00:54:17.940
They are going to work
with these individuals,

00:54:17.940 --> 00:54:19.830
much like Rosa Lee
and her grandfather,

00:54:19.830 --> 00:54:21.570
in a way that I, or
any of my colleagues,

00:54:21.570 --> 00:54:23.190
will never be able to do.

00:54:23.190 --> 00:54:24.690
And so we want to
see more and more

00:54:24.690 --> 00:54:28.170
of these deaf professionals,
deaf interpreters.

00:54:28.170 --> 00:54:30.638
That field needs to
expand exponentially

00:54:30.638 --> 00:54:33.180
to be able to serve the aging
population, especially the baby

00:54:33.180 --> 00:54:37.380
boomers in however many years.

00:54:37.380 --> 00:54:39.480
- We are over time, so
we will wrap up now.

00:54:39.480 --> 00:54:41.520
This is how you clap in ASL.

